## Literature Review (Expanded)\
\
### Biomedical segmentation foundations\
\
U-Net introduced a highly effective encoder-decoder architecture with skip connections for biomedical segmentation, enabling precise localization with limited training data (Ronneberger et al., 2015). U-Net++ extends this with nested dense skip pathways that reduce semantic mismatch between encoder and decoder features, often improving small-structure and boundary-sensitive segmentation tasks (Zhou et al., 2018). For wound boundary estimation, this architectural family is particularly suitable because irregular lesion borders require both high-level context and fine edge detail.\
\
### Efficient scaling and transfer learning\
\
EfficientNet and EfficientNetV2 introduced principled model scaling and training efficiency gains, enabling strong performance with fewer parameters and lower compute than many conventional backbones (Tan & Le, 2019; Tan & Le, 2021). In medium-sized medical image datasets, transfer learning from ImageNet pretraining often stabilizes optimization and improves convergence, especially when combined with augmentations and regularization.\
\
### DFU and wound imaging research context\
\
Prior DFU work demonstrates that deep learning methods can detect ulcers and segment wounds with promising overlap metrics, yet common methodological gaps remain: small cohorts, limited source diversity, weak external validation, and under-reported fairness analysis. Recent challenge settings and review articles repeatedly show that domain shift across camera devices, care sites, and patient populations can sharply reduce generalization even when internal validation appears strong (Goyal et al., 2020; Yap et al., 2022).\
\
This literature strongly influenced my system design. Instead of maximizing one benchmark metric, the DiaFoot.AI v2 pipeline is intentionally data-centric and evaluation-centric: strict split governance, leakage checks, subgroup analysis, and external validation are treated as required components.\
\
### Data governance and AI ethics in healthcare-adjacent CV\
\
Responsible AI guidance and medical AI governance frameworks emphasize transparency, reproducibility, fairness monitoring, and explicit communication of intended use limitations (WHO, 2021). Even in academic projects, risk controls are necessary: dataset documentation, uncertainty handling, and clear non-clinical disclaimers should accompany all performance reporting.\
\
In this project, governance is implemented through operational artifacts (leakage audits, calibration summaries, shortcut stress tests, subgroup reports, and reproducibility bundles), not only narrative discussion.\
\
### Synthesis and gap alignment\
\
The literature supports four key design conclusions used in this project:\
\
1. **Task decomposition is justified:** triage and segmentation are distinct and benefit from specialized models.\
2. **Data quality can outweigh model complexity:** better curation and composition may outperform bigger architectures.\
3. **External robustness must be measured:** internal scores alone are insufficient for trustworthy claims.\
4. **Ethics belongs in the pipeline:** fairness and governance should be evaluated with the same rigor as accuracy.\
\
